%N A392201 Positive k such that the quadratic Diophantine equation x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = k * (x*y - x*z + y*z) has nontrivial integer solutions.
%C A392201 Nontrivial integer solutions of the quadratic Diophantine equation (QDE) x^2+y^2+z^2 = k*(x*y-x*z+y*z), where k >= 2, exist if and only if the squarefree part of (k-2)*(k+1) contains no prime factors of the form 3*j+2.
%C A392201 In particular, all k of the form n^2+2, n >= 0, belong to the sequence, while the set of the corresponding QDE solutions is infinite and it contains, e.g., x=n, y=1, z=1.
%C A392201 From the substitution y -> -y it follows that -a(n) provides all negative k such that (x^2 + y^2 + z^2)/(x*y + y*z + x*z) = k for some integers x, y and z, thus extending A331605 in the negative direction.
%H A392201 Michael Shmoish, <a href="/A392201/a392201.r.txt">R program for A392201</a>
%F A392201 a(n) = A331605(n) - 1.
%e A392201 For n = 5, a(5) = 15 is the first term of the sequence which is not of the form n^2+2. One of the corresponding QDE solutions is x=5, y=7, z=41.
%o A392201 (R) # see linked code
%o A392201 (Python)
%o A392201 from sympy import factorint
%o A392201 def ok(k): return not any(p%3==2 for p, e in factorint((k-2)*(k+1)).items() if e&1)
%o A392201 print([k for k in range(604) if ok(k)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jan 10 2026
